[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The time complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|+|E|)$ , as every vertex and every edge will be explored in the worst case. $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ is the number of edges in the graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Note that $O(|E|)$ may vary between $O(1)$ and $O(|V|^{2})$ , depending on how sparse the input graph is.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] When the number of vertices in the graph is known ahead of time, and additional data structures are used to determine which vertices have already been added to the queue, the space complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] This is in addition to the space required for the graph itself, which may vary depending on the graph representation used by an implementation of the algorithm.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In the analysis of algorithms, the input to breadth-first search is assumed to be a finite graph, represented as an adjacency list, adjacency matrix, or similar representation.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] However, in the application of graph traversal methods in artificial intelligence the input may be an implicit representation of an infinite graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In this context, a search method is described as being complete if it is guaranteed to find a goal state if one exists.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search is complete, but depth-first search is not.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] When applied to infinite graphs represented implicitly, breadth-first search will eventually find the goal state, but depth first search may get lost in parts of the graph that have no goal state and never return.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/breadth-first-search] An enumeration of the vertices of a graph is said to be a BFS ordering if it is a possible output of the application of BFS to this graph.
