[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **component** of an undirected graph is a connected subgraph that is not part of any larger connected subgraph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The components of any graph partition its vertices into disjoint sets, and are the induced subgraphs of those sets.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] A graph that is itself connected has exactly one component, consisting of the whole graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Components are sometimes called **connected components**.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The number of components in a given graph is an important graph invariant, and is closely related to invariants of matroids, topological spaces, and matrices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In random graphs, a frequently occurring phenomenon is the incidence of a giant component, one component that is significantly larger than the others; and of a percolation threshold, an edge probability above which a giant component exists and below which it does not.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The components of a graph can be constructed in linear time, and a special case of the problem, connected-component labeling, is a basic technique in image analysis.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Dynamic connectivity algorithms maintain components as edges are inserted or deleted in a graph, in low time per change.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In computational complexity theory, connected components have been used to study algorithms with limited space complexity, and sublinear time algorithms can accurately estimate the number of components.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] A component of a given undirected graph may be defined as a connected subgraph that is not part of any larger connected subgraph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] For instance, the graph shown in the first illustration has three components.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Every vertex v of a graph belongs to one of the graph's components, which may be found as the induced subgraph of the set of vertices reachable from v .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Every graph is the disjoint union of its components.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Another definition of components involves the equivalence classes of an equivalence relation defined on the graph's vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In an undirected graph, a vertex v is *reachable* from a vertex u if there is a path from u to v , or equivalently a walk (a path allowing repeated vertices and edges).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The equivalence classes of this relation partition the vertices of the graph into disjoint sets, subsets of vertices that are all reachable from each other, with no additional reachable pairs outside of any of these subsets.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Each vertex belongs to exactly one equivalence class.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The components are then the induced subgraphs formed by each of these equivalence classes.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Alternatively, some sources define components as the sets of vertices rather than as the subgraphs they induce.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Similar definitions involving equivalence classes have been used to defined components for other forms of graph connectivity, including the weak components and strongly connected components of directed graphs and the biconnected components of undirected graphs.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The number of components of a given finite graph can be used to count the number of edges in its spanning forests: In a graph with n vertices and c components, every spanning forest will have exactly $n-c$ edges.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] This number $n-c$ is the matroid-theoretic rank of the graph, and the rank of its graphic matroid.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The rank of the dual cographic matroid equals the circuit rank of the graph, the minimum number of edges that must be removed from the graph to break all its cycles.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In a graph with m edges, n vertices and c components, the circuit rank is $m-n+c$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] A graph can be interpreted as a topological space in multiple ways, for instance by placing its vertices as points in general position in three-dimensional Euclidean space and representing its edges as line segments between those points.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The components of a graph can be generalized through these interpretations as the topological connected components of the corresponding space; these are equivalence classes of points that cannot be separated by pairs of disjoint closed sets.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Just as the number of connected components of a topological space is an important topological invariant, the zeroth Betti number, the number of components of a graph is an important graph invariant, and in topological graph theory it can be interpreted as the zeroth Betti number of the graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The number of components arises in other ways in graph theory as well.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In algebraic graph theory it equals the multiplicity of 0 as an eigenvalue of the Laplacian matrix of a finite graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] It is also the index of the first nonzero coefficient of the chromatic polynomial of the graph, and the chromatic polynomial of the whole graph can be obtained as the product of the polynomials of its components.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Numbers of components play a key role in Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings characterizing finite graphs that have perfect matchings and the associated Tutte–Berge formula for the size of a maximum matching, and in the definition of graph toughness.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] It is straightforward to compute the components of a finite graph in linear time (in terms of the numbers of the vertices and edges of the graph) using either breadth-first search or depth-first search.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In either case, a search that begins at some particular vertex v will find the entire component containing v (and no more) before returning.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] All components of a graph can be found by looping through its vertices, starting a new breadth-first or depth-first search whenever the loop reaches a vertex that has not already been included in a previously found component.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Hopcroft & Tarjan (1973) describe essentially this algorithm, and state that it was already "well known".
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Connected-component labeling, a basic technique in computer image analysis, involves the construction of a graph from the image and component analysis on the graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The vertices are the subset of the pixels of the image, chosen as being of interest or as likely to be part of depicted objects.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Edges connect adjacent pixels, with adjacency defined either orthogonally according to the Von Neumann neighborhood, or both orthogonally and diagonally according to the Moore neighborhood.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Identifying the connected components of this graph allows additional processing to find more structure in those parts of the image or identify what kind of object is depicted.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Researchers have developed component-finding algorithms specialized for this type of graph, allowing it to be processed in pixel order rather than in the more scattered order that would be generated by breadth-first or depth-first searching.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] This can be useful in situations where sequential access to the pixels is more efficient than random access, either because the image is represented in a hierarchical way that does not permit fast random access or because sequential access produces better memory access patterns.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] These algorithms take amortized time $O(\alpha (n))$ per operation, where adding vertices and edges and determining the component in which a vertex falls are both operations, and $\alpha$ is a very slowly growing inverse of the very quickly growing Ackermann function.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] When both edge insertions and edge deletions are allowed, dynamic connectivity algorithms can still maintain the same information, in amortized time $O(\log ^{2}n/\log \log n)$ per change and time $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ per connectivity query, or in near-logarithmic randomized expected time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Components of graphs have been used in computational complexity theory to study the power of Turing machines that have a working memory limited to a logarithmic number of bits, with the much larger input accessible only through read access rather than being modifiable.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The problems that can be solved by machines limited in this way define the complexity class L.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] It was finally proven in 2008 that this connectivity problem can be solved in logarithmic space, and therefore that SL = L.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In a graph represented as an adjacency list, with random access to its vertices, it is possible to estimate the number of connected components, with constant probability of obtaining additive (absolute) error at most $\varepsilon n$ , in sublinear time $O(\varepsilon ^{-2}\log \varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In random graphs the sizes of components are given by a random variable, which, in turn, depends on the specific model of how random graphs are chosen.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The connectivity of this model depends on p , and there are three different ranges of p with very different behavior from each other.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In the analysis below, all outcomes occur with high probability, meaning that the probability of the outcome is arbitrarily close to one for sufficiently large values of n .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The analysis depends on a parameter $\varepsilon$ , a positive constant independent of n that can be arbitrarily close to zero.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] , all components are simple and very small.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The largest component has logarithmic size.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Most of its components are trees: the number of vertices in components that have cycles grows more slowly than any unbounded function of the number of vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] Every tree of fixed size occurs linearly many times.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] The remaining components are small, with logarithmic size.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] In the same model of random graphs, there will exist multiple connected components with high probability for values of p below a significantly higher threshold, $p<(1-\varepsilon )(\log n)/n$ , and a single connected component for values above the threshold, $p>(1+\varepsilon )(\log n)/n$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] This phenomenon is closely related to the coupon collector's problem: in order to be connected, a random graph needs enough edges for each vertex to be incident to at least one edge.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] More precisely, if random edges are added one by one to a graph, then with high probability the first edge whose addition connects the whole graph touches the last isolated vertex.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] For different models including the random subgraphs of grid graphs, the connected components are described by percolation theory.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/component-graph-theory] A key question in this theory is the existence of a percolation threshold, a critical probability above which a giant component (or infinite component) exists and below which it does not.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] In computer science, **graph traversal** (also known as **graph search**) refers to the process of visiting (checking and/or updating) each vertex in a graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the vertices are visited.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Tree traversal is a special case of graph traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Unlike tree traversal, graph traversal may require that some vertices be visited more than once, since it is not necessarily known before transitioning to a vertex that it has already been explored.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] As graphs become more dense, this redundancy becomes more prevalent, causing computation time to increase; as graphs become more sparse, the opposite holds true.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Thus, it is usually necessary to remember which vertices have already been explored by the algorithm, so that vertices are revisited as infrequently as possible (or in the worst case, to prevent the traversal from continuing indefinitely).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This may be accomplished by associating each vertex of the graph with a "color" or "visitation" state during the traversal, which is then checked and updated as the algorithm visits each vertex.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] If the vertex has already been visited, it is ignored and the path is pursued no further; otherwise, the algorithm checks/updates the vertex and continues down its current path.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Several special cases of graphs imply the visitation of other vertices in their structure, and thus do not require that visitation be explicitly recorded during the traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] An important example of this is a tree: during a traversal it may be assumed that all "ancestor" vertices of the current vertex (and others depending on the algorithm) have already been visited.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Both the depth-first and breadth-first graph searches are adaptations of tree-based algorithms, distinguished primarily by the lack of a structurally determined "root" vertex and the addition of a data structure to record the traversal's visitation state.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Note. — If each vertex in a graph is to be traversed by a tree-based algorithm (such as DFS or BFS), then the algorithm must be called at least once for each connected component of the graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This is easily accomplished by iterating through all the vertices of the graph, performing the algorithm on each vertex that is still unvisited when examined.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A depth-first search (DFS) is an algorithm for traversing a finite graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] DFS visits the child vertices before visiting the sibling vertices; that is, it traverses the depth of any particular path before exploring its breadth.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A stack (often the program's call stack via recursion) is generally used when implementing the algorithm.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm begins with a chosen "root" vertex; it then iteratively transitions from the current vertex to an adjacent, unvisited vertex, until it can no longer find an unexplored vertex to transition to from its current location.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm then backtracks along previously visited vertices, until it finds a vertex connected to yet more uncharted territory.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] It will then proceed down the new path as it had before, backtracking as it encounters dead-ends, and ending only when the algorithm has backtracked past the original "root" vertex from the very first step.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] DFS is the basis for many graph-related algorithms, including topological sorts and planarity testing.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A breadth-first search (BFS) is another technique for traversing a finite graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] BFS visits the sibling vertices before visiting the child vertices, and a queue is used in the search process.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This algorithm is often used to find the shortest path from one vertex to another.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The problem of graph exploration can be seen as a variant of graph traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] It is an online problem, meaning that the information about the graph is only revealed during the runtime of the algorithm.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A common model is as follows: given a connected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with non-negative edge weights.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm starts at some vertex, and knows all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end of these edges—but not more.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] When a new vertex is visited, then again all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end are known.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The goal is to visit all *n* vertices and return to the starting vertex, but the sum of the weights of the tour should be as small as possible.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The problem can also be understood as a specific version of the travelling salesman problem, where the salesman has to discover the graph on the go.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A *universal traversal sequence* is a sequence of instructions comprising a graph traversal for any regular graph with a set number of vertices and for any starting vertex.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A probabilistic proof was used by Aleliunas et al. to show that there exists a universal traversal sequence with number of instructions proportional to *O*(*n*5) for any regular graph with *n* vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The steps specified in the sequence are relative to the current node, not absolute.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] For example, if the current node is *v**j*, and *v**j* has *d* neighbors, then the traversal sequence will specify the next node to visit, *v**j*+1, as the *i*th neighbor of *v**j*, where 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *d*.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a queue is an abstract data type that serves as an ordered collection of entities.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] By convention, the end of the queue where elements are added is called the back, tail, or rear of the queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The end of the queue where elements are removed is called the head or front of the queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The name *queue* is an analogy to the words used to describe people in line to wait for goods or services.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Other operations may also be allowed, often including a *peek* or *front* operation that returns the value of the next element to be dequeued without dequeuing it.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The operations of a queue make it a first-in-first-out (FIFO) data structure as the first element added to the queue is the first one removed.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] This is equivalent to the requirement that once a new element is added, all elements that were added before have to be removed before the new element can be removed.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] A queue is an example of a linear data structure, or more abstractly a sequential collection.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues are common in computer programs, where they are implemented as data structures coupled with access routines, as an abstract data structure or in object-oriented languages as classes.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] A queue may be implemented as circular buffers and linked lists, or by using both the stack pointer and the base pointer.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues provide services in computer science, transport, and operations research where various entities such as data, objects, persons, or events are stored and held to be processed later.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] In these contexts, the queue performs the function of a buffer.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Another usage of queues is in the implementation of breadth-first search.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Theoretically, one characteristic of a queue is that it does not have a specific capacity.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Regardless of how many elements are already contained, a new element can always be added.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] It can also be empty, at which point removing an element will be impossible until a new element has been added again.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Fixed-length arrays are limited in capacity, but it is not true that items need to be copied towards the head of the queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The simple trick of turning the array into a closed circle and letting the head and tail drift around endlessly in that circle makes it unnecessary to ever move items stored in the array.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] If n is the size of the array, then computing indices modulo n will turn the array into a circle.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The array size must be declared ahead of time, but some implementations simply double the declared array size when overflow occurs.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Most modern languages with objects or pointers can implement or come with libraries for dynamic lists.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Such data structures may have not specified a fixed capacity limit besides memory constraints.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Queue *overflow* results from trying to add an element onto a full queue and queue *underflow* happens when trying to remove an element from an empty queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] A *bounded queue* is a queue limited to a fixed number of items.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] There are several efficient implementations of FIFO queues.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] An efficient implementation is one that can perform the operations—en-queuing and de-queuing—in O(1) time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues may be implemented as a separate data type, or maybe considered a special case of a double-ended queue (deque) and not implemented separately.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] For example, Perl and Ruby allow pushing and popping an array from both ends, so one can use **push** and **shift** functions to enqueue and dequeue a list (or, in reverse, one can use **unshift** and **pop**), although in some cases these operations are not efficient.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] C++'s Standard Template Library provides a "`queue`" templated class which is restricted to only push/pop operations.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Since J2SE5.0, Java's library contains a `Queue` interface that specifies queue operations; implementing classes include `LinkedList` and (since J2SE 1.6) `ArrayDeque`.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] PHP has an SplQueue class and third-party libraries like beanstalk'd and Gearman.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues can also be implemented as a purely functional data structure.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The first one only achieves $O(1)$ per operation *on average*.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] That is, the amortized time is $O(1)$ , but individual operations can take $O(n)$ where *n* is the number of elements in the queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The second implementation is called a **real-time queue** and it allows the queue to be persistent with operations in O(1) worst-case time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] It is a more complex implementation and requires lazy lists with memoization.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] This queue's data is stored in two singly-linked lists named f and r .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The list f holds the front part of the queue.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The list r holds the remaining elements (a.k.a., the rear of the queue) *in reverse order*.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] It is easy to insert into the front of the queue by adding a node at the head of f .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] And, if r is not empty, it is easy to remove from the end of the queue by removing the node at the head of r .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] When r is empty, the list f is reversed and assigned to r and then the head of r is removed.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The insert ("enqueue") always takes $O(1)$ time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The removal ("dequeue") takes $O(1)$ when the list r is not empty.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] When r is empty, the reverse takes $O(n)$ where n is the number of elements in f .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] But, we can say it is $O(1)$ amortized time, because every element in f had to be inserted and we can assign a constant cost for each element in the reverse to when it was inserted.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The real-time queue achieves $O(1)$ time for all operations, without amortization.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] This discussion will be technical, so recall that, for l a list, $|l|$ denotes its length, that *NIL* represents an empty list and $\operatorname {CONS} (h,t)$ represents the list whose head is *h* and whose tail is *t*.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The data structure used to implement our queues consists of three singly-linked lists $(f,r,s)$ where *f* is the front of the queue and *r* is the rear of the queue in reverse order.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The invariant of the structure is that *s* is the rear of *f* without its $|r|$ first elements, that is $|s|=|f|-|r|$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The tail of the queue $(\operatorname {CONS} (x,f),r,s)$ is then almost $(f,r,s)$ and inserting an element *x* to $(f,r,s)$ is almost $(f,\operatorname {CONS} (x,r),s)$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] It is said almost, because in both of those results, $|s|=|f|-|r|+1$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] An auxiliary function $aux$ must then be called for the invariant to be satisfied.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Two cases must be considered, depending on whether s is the empty list, in which case $|r|=|f|+1$ , or not.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Let us call $\operatorname {reverse} (f,r)$ the function which returns *f* followed by *r* reversed.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Let us furthermore assume that $|r|=|f|+1$ , since it is the case when this function is called.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] More precisely, we define a lazy function $\operatorname {rotate} (f,r,a)$ which takes as input three lists such that $|r|=|f|+1$ , and return the concatenation of *f*, of *r* reversed and of *a*.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Then $\operatorname {reverse} (f,r)=\operatorname {rotate} (f,r,{\text{NIL}})$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Its running time is $O(r)$ , but, since lazy evaluation is used, the computation is delayed until the results are forced by the computation.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] The list *s* in the data structure has two purposes.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] This list serves as a counter for $|f|-|r|$ , indeed, $|f|=|r|$ if and only if *s* is the empty list.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] This counter allows us to ensure that the rear is never longer than the front list.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Furthermore, using *s*, which is a tail of *f*, forces the computation of a part of the (lazy) list *f* during each *tail* and *insert* operation.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] Therefore, when $|f|=|r|$ , the list *f* is totally forced.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/queue-abstract-data-type] If it was not the case, the internal representation of *f* could be some append of append of... of append, and forcing would not be a constant time operation anymore.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/shortest-path-problem] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In computer science, **tree traversal** (also known as **tree search** and **walking the tree**) is a form of graph traversal and refers to the process of visiting (e.g. retrieving, updating, or deleting) each node in a tree data structure exactly once.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the nodes are visited.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The following algorithms are described for a binary tree, but they may be generalized to other trees as well.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Unlike linked lists, one-dimensional arrays and other linear data structures, which are canonically traversed in linear order, trees may be traversed in multiple ways.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] They may be traversed in depth-first or breadth-first order.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are three common ways to traverse them in depth-first order: in-order, pre-order and post-order.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Beyond these basic traversals, various more complex or hybrid schemes are possible, such as depth-limited searches like iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The latter, as well as breadth-first search, can also be used to traverse infinite trees, see below.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Traversing a tree involves iterating over all nodes in some manner.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Because from a given node there is more than one possible next node (it is not a linear data structure), then, assuming sequential computation (not parallel), some nodes must be deferred—stored in some way for later visiting.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This is often done via a stack (LIFO) or queue (FIFO).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] As a tree is a self-referential (recursively defined) data structure, traversal can be defined by recursion or, more subtly, corecursion, in a natural and clear fashion; in these cases the deferred nodes are stored implicitly in the call stack.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Depth-first search is easily implemented via a stack, including recursively (via the call stack), while breadth-first search is easily implemented via a queue, including corecursively.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In *depth-first search* (DFS), the search tree is deepened as much as possible before going to the next sibling.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Execute the following three operations in a certain order: N: Visit the current node.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] L: Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] R: Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The trace of a traversal is called a sequentialisation of the tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The traversal trace is a list of each visited node.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] No one sequentialisation according to pre-, in- or post-order describes the underlying tree uniquely.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Given a tree with distinct elements, either pre-order or post-order paired with in-order is sufficient to describe the tree uniquely.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] However, pre-order with post-order leaves some ambiguity in the tree structure.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are three methods at which position of the traversal relative to the node (in the figure: red, green, or blue) the visit of the node shall take place.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The choice of exactly one color determines exactly one visit of a node as described below.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The pre-order traversal is a topologically sorted one, because a parent node is processed before any of its child nodes is done.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position blue).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can be useful to get postfix expression of a binary expression tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position green).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *ascending* sorted order.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, reverse in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *descending* sorted order.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for pre-order traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for in-order traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's last subtree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for post-order traversal.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Depending on the problem at hand, pre-order, post-order, and especially one of the number of subtrees − 1 in-order operations may be optional.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Also, in practice more than one of pre-order, post-order, and in-order operations may be required.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, when inserting into a ternary tree, a pre-order operation is performed by comparing items.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A post-order operation may be needed afterwards to re-balance the tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In *breadth-first search* (BFS) or *level-order search*, the search tree is broadened as much as possible before going to the next depth.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are also tree traversal algorithms that classify as neither depth-first search nor breadth-first search.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] One such algorithm is Monte Carlo tree search, which concentrates on analyzing the most promising moves, basing the expansion of the search tree on random sampling of the search space.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal can be used to make a prefix expression (Polish notation) from expression trees: traverse the expression tree pre-orderly.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in pre-order yields "+ * *A* − *B* *C* + *D* *E*".
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In prefix notation, there is no need for any parentheses as long as each operator has a fixed number of operands.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal is also used to create a copy of the tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can generate a postfix representation (Reverse Polish notation) of a binary tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in post-order yields "*A* *B* *C* − * *D* *E* + +"; the latter can easily be transformed into machine code to evaluate the expression by a stack machine.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal is also used to delete the tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Each node is freed after freeing its children.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In-order traversal is very commonly used on binary search trees because it returns values from the underlying set in order, according to the comparator that set up the binary search tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Below are examples of stack-based implementation for pre-order, post-order and in-order traversal in recursive approach (left) as well as iterative approach (right).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Implementations in iterative approach are able to avoid the drawbacks of recursion, particularly limitations of stack space and performance issues.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Several alternative implementations are also mentioned.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The `node` to be started with may have been found in the binary search tree `bst` by means of a standard **search** function, which is shown here in an implementation without parent pointers, i.e. it uses a `stack` for holding the ancestor pointers.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Note that the function does not use keys, which means that the sequential structure is completely recorded by the binary search tree’s edges.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For traversals without change of direction, the (amortised) average complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(1),$ because a full traversal takes $2n-2$ steps for a BST of size $n,$ 1 step for edge up and 1 for edge down.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The worst-case complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(h)$ with h as the height of the tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] All the above implementations require stack space proportional to the height of the tree which is a call stack for the recursive and a parent (ancestor) stack for the iterative ones.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a poorly balanced tree, this can be considerable.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] With the iterative implementations we can remove the stack requirement by maintaining parent pointers in each node, or by threading the tree (next section).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A binary tree is threaded by making every left child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order predecessor of the node (if it exists) and every right child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order successor of the node (if it exists).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] We can make only one traversal at a time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] It is more prone to errors when both the children are not present and both values of nodes point to their ancestors.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Revert the changes to restore original tree.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Also, listed below is pseudocode for a simple queue based level-order traversal, and will require space proportional to the maximum number of nodes at a given depth.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This can be as much as half the total number of nodes.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A more space-efficient approach for this type of traversal can be implemented using an iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] While traversal is usually done for trees with a finite number of nodes (and hence finite depth and finite branching factor) it can also be done for infinite trees.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This is of particular interest in functional programming (particularly with lazy evaluation), as infinite data structures can often be easily defined and worked with, though they are not (strictly) evaluated, as this would take infinite time.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Some finite trees are too large to represent explicitly, such as the game tree for chess or Go, and so it is useful to analyze them as if they were infinite.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A basic requirement for traversal is to visit every node eventually.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For infinite trees, simple algorithms often fail this.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, given a binary tree of infinite depth, a depth-first search will go down one side (by convention the left side) of the tree, never visiting the rest, and indeed an in-order or post-order traversal will never visit *any* nodes, as it has not reached a leaf (and in fact never will).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first (level-order) traversal will traverse a binary tree of infinite depth without problem, and indeed will traverse any tree with bounded branching factor.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first search will never reach the grandchildren, as it seeks to exhaust the children first.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A more sophisticated analysis of running time can be given via infinite ordinal numbers; for example, the breadth-first search of the depth 2 tree above will take ω·2 steps: ω for the first level, and then another ω for the second level.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Thus, simple depth-first or breadth-first searches do not traverse every infinite tree, and are not efficient on very large trees.
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] However, hybrid methods can traverse any (countably) infinite tree, essentially via a diagonal argument ("diagonal"—a combination of vertical and horizontal—corresponds to a combination of depth and breadth).
[src:breadth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Concretely, given the infinitely branching tree of infinite depth, label the root (), the children of the root (1), (2), ..., the grandchildren (1, 1), (1, 2), ..., (2, 1), (2, 2), ..., and so on.
